headline.main: News from Havana.; THE SLAVE-TRADE--LOSS OF THE SLAVER 'P. SOULE'--REPORTED THREATS AGAINST THE CAPTAIN-GENERAL'S LIFE--MOVEMENTS OF THE BRITISH WEST INDIA SQUADRON--BUSINESS-HEALTH OF HAVANA, ETC.

docs.lead_paragraph: The brig P. Soule, formerly a packet between this port and New-Orleans, was sold two years since to the Mazora Company of slave-traders, and has made three successful voyages, and landed her last cargo a few days since in the bay of Cabafias, or that vicinity, six landred Africans, of which no one knows anything, although the fact is notorious in this community.

headline.main: NEW-YORK CITY.; Quarantined, but Resigned THOMPSON, our Health Officer, gave ?? October Temperature. Sudden Death. The Harbor Commissioners. Cricket.

docs.lead_paragraph: Dr. THOMPSON, our Health Officer, gave a lunch to sundry of his friends on Saturday, of the order which has so often distinguished his hospitality. The solid materials for a thorough palatal gratification were abundant, as one would expect who remembers that there are several fine fruit orchards and magnificent gardens somewhat eastward of Quarantine, and that few boats come up from that quarter without saluting the yellow flag.

headline.main: LONG ISLAND.; The Yellow Fever in Kings County.

docs.lead_paragraph: Considerable excitement has prevailed in Brooklyn for several days past about the yellow fever, but without any other real cause than may be found in the fact that the boundaries of the infected district have been gradually enlarged, and now embrace almost the whole water front from Fort Hamilton to within a block of Fulton Ferry. headline.main: NEWS FROM HAVANA.; Arrival of the Quaker City.

docs.lead_paragraph: The steamship Quaker City, Capt. SHUFELDT, from Mobile; 22d inst., at noon-and Havana 24th, at 5 P. M.,--arrived here yesterday afternoon, four days from the latter port. From Havana, we learn that the health of that city had very much improved, and no fears are now entertained from the Yellow Fever.

docs.lead_paragraph: Miss CATHERINE HAYES has arrived in Paris, to enjoy a season of repose, after her long journeyings in the Antipodes, the two Americans, and the East Indies. Mr. THACKERAY is at present on the Continent, fast recovering his health, which was not good since his return from America last Spring.

headline.main: THE LOSS OF THE STEAMER NIAGARA.; Further Particulars--From Fifty to Seventyfive Lives Lost.

docs.lead_paragraph: The terrible news reached this city, this morning, by a telegraphic dispatch to the Collingwood office, and later by the steamer Traveler, from Sheboygan, of the conflagration of the steamer Niagara, bound for Chicago, with a loss of from fifty to seventy five passengers. We immediately proceeded to the Traveler, and gathered the following particulars from passengers who were on board, and brought down by that boat.
